author: Adam Grose MA RWAAN
title: Napoleonic War Veteran
description: The painting is a portrait of a veteran from the Napoleonic war. Throughout time man has fought other countries over power, resources, control, defense and ego. I sought out images from wars of the past. seeking images of soldiers who had given their time and their life fighting for those in power. On the website Retronaut I came across images of Napoleonic soldiers and decided to paint a few images as portraits, keeping their identity anonymous, only allowing their uniform and their body language to speak to the viewer.

author: Olena Shtepura
title: Sophie
description: The painting is fully focused on the face of a young woman, to be more precise, around her facial expressions. Olena managed to catch this brief moment when the girl just made an eye contact with someone she liked. Despite her indifferent pose, the girl’s eyes, red cheeks, and a slight smile - are clear signs that some cautious flirting takes place… Clear distinctive brushstrokes and thick layers of paint clearly mean that the artist was focused to transfer to the viewer the essence of the object rather than any details, which is very typical for impressionism and post impressionism.

author: Victoria Alferonok
title: Landscape with Sculpture
description: " Landscape with Sculpture" is a plein air oil on canvas study. It's filled with the light of a sunny summer evening, playing with glints and shadows in the canopy of an ancient oak. A snow-white sculpture, seemingly accidentally present on the street of a small town, brings a sense of mystery and elegance to the composition. This study is an invitation to pause and breathe deeply, to feel the full spectrum and richness of the green color, to immerse oneself in the tranquility and harmony of the moment.

author: James Earley
title: Shame
description: Look at Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan, The Yemen. The list goes on, never ends. Children cry and scream as the planes get louder and louder as they approach, drones buzz in the air desperate to kill. It never stops. "We do it to protect human rights and restore democracy" the leaders of the west say with a smile on their face whilst behind closed doors they look at the oil costs, they look at the stock market price of the weapons manufacturers, they look at their bank balance. Shame on them.

Each piece takes takes quite a while to create since each individual layer is worked on and must dry before applying the next. Unfortunately there is no way a scan or photograph can capture the true beauty of this piece but I have done the best that I can to show the shimmer and sparkles. The girl in the foreground is having a leisurely wander through the famous market. The house where Matisse lived and worked is in the background on the right. Deep shadows fall against the ground and under the cafe awnings. I painted this after a recent visit to Nice as I was so inspired by the light and colours. The market was wonderful and full of colour. Lavender, herbs, cheese, vegetables, flowers, and art were all for sale.

description: " Landscape with Sculpture" is a plein air oil on canvas study. It's filled with the light of a sunny summer evening, playing with glints and shadows in the canopy of an ancient oak. A snow-white sculpture, seemingly accidentally present on the street of a small town, brings a sense of mystery and elegance to the composition. This study is an invitation to pause and breathe deeply, to feel the full spectrum and richness of the green color, to immerse oneself in the tranquility and harmony of the moment.

author: James Earley
title: Shame
description: Look at Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan, The Yemen. The list goes on, never ends. Children cry and scream as the planes get louder and louder as they approach, drones buzz in the air desperate to kill. It never stops. "We do it to protect human rights and restore democracy" the leaders of the west say with a smile on their face whilst behind closed doors they look at the oil costs, they look at the stock market price of the weapons manufacturers, they look at their bank balance. Shame on them.

description: This work of art is a mixed media piece that was created with many layers over time and a lot of experimenting. The process to create these pieces took a long to time to perfect and I believe it to be unique and unlike anything else out there. Each piece takes takes quite a while to create since each individual layer is worked on and must dry before applying the next. Unfortunately there is no way a scan or photograph can capture the true beauty of this piece but I have done the best that I can to show the shimmer and sparkles.  Vibrant in color and you can actually look through the layers in this piece as well as the wonderful texture. The wood has been burned and then sealed. Comes ready to hang right out of the package.

author: Troy Hyde
title: Felix
description: Make a statement with this contemporary figurative painting. Felix, observed from life by the London-based artist Troy Hyde, has been hand-painted with Winsor & Newton gouache onto the highest quality 100% cotton fibre fine art paper. The result is a black so deep you could fall in it. The vellum-like paper is heavyweight 250gsm with two deckle edges along the left and right sides. Accompanied by an authenticity certificate stamped and signed by the artist and must remain with the work.

author: Helen Maxfield
title: Suffolk Coastline
description: The view from Dunwich beach looking South towards Sizewell. I was struck by a feeling of the area being at a pivotal moment in history; standing with my back to Minsmere nature reserve, a site dedicated to protecting our precious wildlife and looking out towards Sizewell power station. From my viewpoint it sits between offshore wind turbines and pylons on the horizon. So much to take in and consider…

description: From my Floating World series, the Paper Courtesans fuse my love of  Japanese Ukiyo-e (“pictures of the floating world”) woodblock prints and my fascination with unusual spaces. My images are attempts to fix these fugitive elements on paper; to create images both beautiful and surreal.

author: Linda Clerget
title: Abstract impressionist landscape painting, " And came the time of the fairies "
description: This series of paintings is inspired by the relationship between the artist and the forest of Fontainebleau. Every day, the artist goes there to make sketches, to walk, to dialogue with the forest. The initial sketches are made on the spot in different mediums (watercolor, pencil, gouache, ink, pastels). These are notes that will be used later to create from these traces and the memory of the moment lived with the place. The final painting is then done in the studio. The canvas is varnished and ready to hang. It is delivered with its certificate of authenticity signed by the artist.

This message is addressed to every human being with sincere compassion from the bottom of my heart.

author: Ole Karako
title: Embankment in Kyiv
description: This painting was done en plein air. I spent a long time searching for the right view for my artwork but couldn't find it. There was an abundance of cottonwood fluff on Trukhanov Island that kept getting into my eyes and nose without permission. I ventured a bit deeper into the island, only to be greeted by swarms of mosquitoes. Disheartened, I made my way along the pedestrian bridge, constantly brushing off the cottonwood fluff from my face. After crossing to the other bank, I sat down to rest on the embankment—and there, I witnessed the most exquisite hues of a pearlescent sunset. I quickly started painting, as twilight fades away so swiftly...

author: Sumit Mehndiratta
title: Nailed it Series No. 26
description: I like creating geometrical patterns through various mediums. I like them to be precise in terms of their shape and construction. Using threads and nails has been one of the many creative ways I could use to make geometrical shapes and have fun with them. Each nail is hammered separately and then I weave the threads through the nails one by one by hand until I get the desired shape and its placement onto the sculpture. Together these shapes create a beautiful complexity and the fine lines of threads mixing with each other create a beautiful, intricate pattern. Around 200 yards of thread is used in this artwork.

author: Janice MacDougall
title: Bonny Bits Cottage
description: This is an original watercolour painting, painted on good quality watercolour paper, which measures 19x28cm. It comes unmounted and unframed allowing you to choose a frame in your own style. It features a beautiful Cumbrian cottage in the village of Garrigill, it’s named Bonny bits cottage after the fluorite, quartz and calcite crystals found when mining lead in the area. The miners used to call these the “Bonny bits” and decorated their homes and made dioramas out of them which can be seen at the Killhope mining museum in Weardale. It will be posted via Royal Mail signed for delivery in a cardboard backed envelope.  If you would like me to paint something similar, please don't hesitate to contact me.

author: Dora Stork
title: Europe in Pécs (Hot wax on OSB)
description: The city of Pécs (Hungary), where I grew up became one of the Europe's cultural capitals in 2010. The picture shows the Zsolnay-well with the inevitable pigeons. I like this well, whose 4 bull heads are made in the shape of an ancient gold cup. They are finished with special glaze, the eosin glaze, which  is the pride of Pécs. These glaze was developed by owner of the Zsolnay porcelain factory in the second half of the 19th century. But the family could not keep the factory in the socialism. They then bought back after the regime change. And now the local powers of the government made the operation of the factory by family Zsolnay impossible again and they got it. Who knows if the production of eosin glaze remains?

author: Andrew  Reid Wildman
title: Regal Corner, Beverley
description: As an infant, I was marched to and from school past the corner where the Regal no longer stands. In rain or in sun, the corner represented the last, or the first, gasp of freedom from the red brick stone tyranny of the school. I was fascinated and a little scared of this huge, semi-derelict Art Deco building, doors already boarded, the screen silver no more. And one day, as I returned as a man, my boyhood over, the cinema was gone, as though perhaps it had never been there at all. This work is a lovely souvenir of Beverley, and a great gift too.

I have used Gold, Silver, and Orange shades with bold palette applications and then I have created Lines going across the center that are White, Shades of Orange and Gold. I like adding a touch of Red as it is Good Luck in China and Japan. In China-Red is considered around happiness & prosperity. In Japan-Red denotes strength, passion, self sacrifice, and blood. I have only added small touches of both to denote the meaning of Red..so I have one small application of Red. There are 2 main layers of paint blending. There are touches of Purple. There are small details in the painting that are hard to pick up with my photographs. The painting can be hung 4 different directions - so there is 2 Vertical hangings and 2 Horizontal hangings. The theme of a seated women, replete with flowers and a Bird is of course a mainstay for me. But it was fun going back to adding decorative papers to create parts of objects, but with areas left, where I painted in similar fashion to finish off the object. When I work in this manner, I always try to keep from copying the paper design too closely, so that it’s it apparent where I’ve painted an “imitation” of a paper’s design. In this piece I utilized Acrylic Paint pens to create many of the smaller details. The  edges of this canvas are painted so that it can be hung, unframed.

author: Amy Smith
title: True Colors
description: In the captivating artwork titled "True Colors," the creative spirit of Robert Rauschenberg and the eco art movement intertwine, resulting in a mixed media masterpiece that exudes both artistic brilliance and social consciousness. The canvas comes alive with curated pieces of recycled magazines, carefully selected to convey a powerful message of environmental advocacy. The artwork pays homage to the valiant "water warriors," symbolizing their tireless efforts to protect our planet's precious resources. Through a graffiti-inspired abstract composition, the painting transcends traditional boundaries, inviting viewers to engage in a profound dialogue about our collective responsibility towards nature. Each brushstroke and collage element becomes a brushstroke of activism, highlighting the urgent need for environmental preservation. "True Colors" serves as a visual testament, reminding us that art has the power to ignite social change and raise awareness about critical issues. It becomes a conduit for expressing our truest values and colors, urging us to embrace our role as stewards of the earth and inspire others to join the cause.

It struck me that this was in contrast to the kind of binary conversations that become infinite, confrontational and lacking direction that happen on social media platforms.

author: Sean Christopher Ward
title: The Dark Gateway
description: “Chromatic Hallucinations” is a body of work that focuses on the ideals of pattern.  It can represent many different things throughout humanity.  The people, the beliefs they follow, the natural world around you, the history of subjects and the traditions that have been followed.  Different colors and shapes vary meanings throughout different cultures, but the idea is carried down from generation to generation.  From birth to death, pattern is a part of everyday life and cultural practice.  The drive to recognize and form patterns can be from a glimpse into curiosity, discovery of new ideas and experimentation through everyday life.  Da Vinci found this “Way of Stimulating and Arousing the Mind to Various Inventions” so invaluable that he applied it not only visually, as a means of inventing landscape or battle scenes, but in musical matters as well.  The more patterns we can recognize, the wider our imaginative and creative scope.  There is a revolution in the science of design under way, and most people, including designers, aren’t even aware it is taking place.  Color, for example, was just researched to find that simply glancing at shades of green can boost creativity and motivation.  It is easy to assume that there is correlation between verdant colors and vegetation capable of bearing food, which would mentally trigger the thought of nourishment.  There is a science between window views of landscapes aiding in patient recovery, learning in classrooms and expanding productivity in the workplace.  Additionally, certain patterns also have a universal appeal.  Humanity responds dramatically to balanced pattern so much so that it has been researched to reduce stress levels by as much as 60 percent, just by being the field of vision of the viewer.

Thanks to unique technique  - cutting a landscape print on straps and shifting the overall picture, his paintings get a fresh, abstract feel and modern vibe. Movement, nature, air, and life itself make a unique mixture. This man-made shift of nature's usual image makes it similar to digital glitches and urban life artifacts. Nature as well as life is changing all the time, and this unstoppable process is depicted in a new bold way in this artworks series.

author: Gina Valenti-Lazarchik
title: Spirit of Ukraine
description: Ever since the invasion began, I've been praying for Ukraine and for her heroic people, who have fought--and who continue to fight like lions--for their freedom.  I hold all of the Ukrainian people in my heart and in my prayers.  I pray for their freedom and sovereignty, and I pray that their great sacrifice will be a source of even greater blessing.  I pray for an end to their fear and suffering.  Someday, the guns will fall silent and the invader will be gone from their land.  Someday--soon, I hope!--they will return to their homes and, with the free world's help, they will rebuild.  The scars of war will be but a memory, and Ukraine will again be free, knowing this was their "finest hour", in the words of Winston Churchill.  This mixed media abstract, with gold leaf accent, is my own personal prayer for a just peace.  It has been given a satin varnish for protection and hanging hardware is already installed.

description: My old wooden dresser had an interesting assortment of old biscuit boxes, one which had Italian biscottis, and n orange teapot. A domestic scene with rustic colours which I was inspired to paint. I like the earthy colours of the wood and the yellow of the sweetcorn and combined with the green and white of the Victorian jug it made an inspiring composition. The Victorian jug stood out from this background filled with the dried sweet corn and flowers. I particularly liked the muted colours which some how reflected the Victorian era. I liked the composition and the close up of the dresser shelves. I sketched it out and enjoyed finishing it off in oils on a stretched canvas. The painting has a textured finish which reflects the antique look.

description: This Original One of a Kind artwork  is called , "The Blissful PEACE of Surrender!"  It is inspired by the lyrics found in the song, "Anxious Heart"  by Jeremy Camp. It is created on a 20 x 16 stretched canvas.  It is also inspired by the song by Ed Sheeran, "Make it Rain!".   When you realize that to fight and struggle in the  life situation you are in is just hopeless.......sometimes Surrender is the only way to find Peace.  There are a  million different battle we humans fight everyday. Most of the time "WE"  are the real problem. We can't do it ourselves but pride or addiction to the struggle keep us from asking for help.  That is what hopelessness is truly  This painting sums it up for me. The young woman gives up trying to fight battles in the STORM in her life and she Surrenders. There she finds Joy in the loss of struggle and the war within herself. She turns her umbrella upside down and takes a nice soak in a pool of rainbow rain falling down softly upon her.   For me it was giving up the struggle and finding Jesus. Surrendered to him. For others it can simply be surrendering to the reality of what they are doing to themselves. Ask for Help from Somebody!!!

author: Olena Koliesnik
title: Time to take off the masks - original watercolor painting
description: The plot of this picture was formed under the reflections that arose in the process of finding oneself.  It is a self-portrait of honesty with oneself.  I wore masks because I wanted to be comfortable.  I killed myself with this deception.  Therefore, in the picture I used the face as a layering of masks, because I was thinking about a masquerade ball.  At such events, faces are hidden and it is impossible to guess who is who.  This work has a related history with my village, where I come from.  The photo reference was created on the territory of the village.  I was born there, but with the events my perception of that native place has undergone changes.  External transformations: the beginning of the war, violence, I did not know how to perceive my native land.  Splitting reality.  All traumatic events affected me as a teenager, and I could not form my point of view on their beginning.  Is this still a house?  Is it just geographical data to determine the natal chart?  Why did the war start from my land?  This painting is a reflection on the uncertainty and fear of never seeing the parental home again.

author: Karin Vermeer
title: Aqua (small resin edition)
description: My work is a mix of different pictures/images and paints which I combine on the computer and canvas to create a new image. My favorite subject is the female face. Most of the portraits that I create are a mix of four to five different faces, mostly of different race and origin. On my computer I create a new, non-existing person out of them. Besides creating and building new persons I also take pictures in my studio of models that I use. Together with these pictures and the pictures of old walls, grunge posters and all kinds of other interesting subjects I create a new image. I also use already existing pictures that I manipulate in photoshop and create a new image with. When the digital part is ready I print the image and start painting over it. I create thick structures and a lot of layers of paint and gel over them. In this way, I try to make the digital image tangible again. My work is not so much about explanation and concept it is a game and all about the image. I start with no idea in general but by looking at images that interest me and by mixing them, slowly a new image evolves.

description: Falling water levels in The Dead Sea. "In recent decades, the Dead Sea has been rapidly shrinking because of diversion of incoming water from the Jordan River to the north. The southern end is fed by a canal maintained by the Dead Sea Works, a company that converts the sea's raw materials. From a water surface of 395 m (1,296 ft) below sea level in 1970 it fell 22 m (72 ft) to 418 m (1,371 ft) below sea level in 2006, reaching a drop rate of 1 m (3 ft) per year. As the water level decreases, the characteristics of the Sea and surrounding region may substantially change."

title: Lost Information
description: When I was a younger artist, I never really thought about branding or identity...my ego sustained me and didn't feel I needed to let anyone know...they should just KNOW. But, as time goes by and the hair gets grayer and life gets calmer and focused, identity seems to be slipping into the fray more than often. I suspect I am at the age where all the reflections on life start happening, and the horrible rumination on legacy/immortality. The latter I abhor and do not like to think about because it sullies the present and the moment. Alas, it creeps in.

author: Gina Valenti-Lazarchik
title: Prayer #3
description: How good of a friendship would you have if you never spoke to or interacted with your friend?  Friendship grows and deepens over time spent, trust extended, joys and pains shared.  The same is true in our relationship with Jesus, as we demonstrate our trust in Him and His central value to us as we consistently set time aside to open our soul to Him, to pray.   I began this pair of paintings by printing various Scripture passages on gold paper (see individual painting descriptions for specific Scripture passages, which are unique to each piece), which I collaged onto the canvas in the shape of a Cross, to express my belief that the impetus to pray comes first from God.  For me, the Bible has been a life-long and inexhaustible source of help, inspiration and comfort, so it’s important to me, as a Christian artist, to center my work on Scripture.  I painted various colors and patterns onto watercolor paper, which I also collaged, to express the fact that prayer carries us through all seasons of life:  joy, pain, doubt, grief, et.  The palette is based upon blue, “true blue” as they say, because blue is associated with trust and fidelity.  Blue and purple are also calming, which is a necessary state of mind, heart and soul to pray effectively.  I chose circles as the main motif because I wanted to express time and eternity:  after all, one revolution of our globe is a day, so a half-circle, therefore, can express our waking hours.  The size of circles shows that sometimes we can allow hours of time to prayer and worship; on other days, perhaps, our prayers are brief (but no less heart-felt).   The paint is intentionally transparent or opaque, as God grants us insight.  If you, or someone you know, feels that prayer is their rock, as I do, then I hope that this pair of paintings will be a visual expression of their on-going and ever deepening relationship with Jesus Christ.  Hanging hardware is already installed, and the paintings have been given a satin varnish for long life and protection.

author: Juan Jose Hoyos Quiles
title: Abstract Movement
description: Most often when I’m painting, I’m listening to classic R&B or smooth jazz. Sometimes this has a direct effect on my work. I feel that “Abstract Symphony” and “Abstract Movement” fall into this category.  Again working in pairs, these two paintings on paper with collage elements  have a “musical” feeling to them. Cool, collected and smooth. Think Cubism meets Jean Arp. Again hard edge geometry meets beautiful colors. I used acrylic paint mixed with a little gesso giving the paint a chalky or pastel look. This work is composed of painted cut paper shapes collaged onto another sheet of paper. Titled, signed and dated on the reverse.

author: Gina Valenti-Lazarchik
title: Down Under
description: This painting is my reflection on the fact that you can't tell, by outward appearance, what might be going on inside another person.  Very few people are what they appear on the surface.  Most people outwardly go about their daily lives, their work and activities, while they inwardly struggle--down under--with an entire landscape of thoughts, concerns, fears, hopes and emotions.  I have presented this inner landscape in abstract form, using a pastel collage, which was mounted on a birch wood panel and then overpainted in oil and cold wax.  The reverse side of the wooden panel has been routed with a "keyhole" for ease of hanging, so no hardware is required.  The painting has been given a satin varnish for protection and long life.

author: Raúl Lara
title: Tempus Fugit I
description: This series is a profound reflection on the fleeting nature of time and its transcendental impact on our lives. It is a moving testament to the ephemeral nature of each moment, as time slips through our fingers like sand in an hourglass. The very title, "Tempus Fugit," derived from an ancient verse written by the illustrious Latin poet Virgil over two millennia ago, resonates with the eternal truth of the swift passage of time. In this artwork, my aim has been to capture the complexity of human emotions and the inherent fragility of our existence.

author: Holly Wojahn
title: Bits and pieces
description: This painting literally started with the idea to cut up an old painting I had hanging around, and Collage my favorite bits  into the composition of this new Piece. Inspired by that idea, I also cut up an old Colored Pencil Drawing, and incorporated parts of that too! I dug out my Caran d’ache  Crayons that I typically use only for making drawings when traveling, and used those mixed in with my beloved Posca Acrylic pens! I incorporated torn bits of French Newspaper, as well as some Patterned Decorative paper. The Result reminds me of a collection of old Buttons, Fabric Scraps, and Costume Jewelry my Mother kept tucked in a beautifully painted metal box, when I was a child. ( Maybe this was the Muse in my head, as I worked on this piece?) The Canvas is painted around the edges so that the Painting can be hung unframed, if preferred…

author: Richard Vloemans
title: Bubbly Blue Waters
description: The explosions in this artwork are made of the colors: Blue, neon turquoise, magenta, violet and dark violet. The artwork has a centered explosion of the same colours. In this artwork the colour blue forms the dominant color. I added some effects with acrylic paint mixed with water and a bottle of degreaser, with which I shape the bubbles that are visible in the artwork.  The colors are applied in several layers on the canvas and mixed with water on the spot. The abstract background consists of the colors that return in the explosion. The structure of the explosion is made by means of palette knives and is wiped out in several layers on the abstract background.

title: Enso Serenity 69 - Enso Abstract painting by Kathy Morton Stanion
description: 'Ensō (円相) is a Japanese word meaning "circle" and a concept strongly associated with Zen. It symbolizes the Absolute, enlightenment, strength, elegance, the Universe, and the void; it can also symbolize the Japanese aesthetic itself. In Zen Buddhist painting, ensō symbolizes a moment when the mind is free to simply let the body/spirit create.'
